summary: New test rapidly identifies antibiotic-resistant ‘superbugs’
title: New test rapidly identifies antibiotic-resistant ‘superbugs’
description: When you get sick, you want the right treatment fast. But certain infectious microbes are experts at evading the very anti-bacterial drugs designed to fight them. A simple and inexpensive new test developed by UC Berkeley researchers can diagnose patients with antibiotic-resistant strains of bacteria in a matter of minutes. via Snapzu : Health & Body

summary: Starting my journey via /r/Fitness
title: Starting my journey via /r/Fitness
body:
I’m 21 (M), 6ft 1 and around 65kg. I’ve been trying to put weight on and have recently been active trying to get fit. I’ve been jogging and doing a lot of bodyweight training at home. I feel like I could benefit from the gym, but a lot of my friends feel that I should ‘get the foundations down’ first - i.e. getting fit at home first before I pay for 'the experience of the gym’.

Is it worth it to just throw myself in there? And also, how have you found it trying to put weight on? There’s a lot of advice out there for losing weight but not much in the way of putting it on for those of us who struggle.

Is a mass gainer worth it in my situation? Do they really work? What else can I do to help? I feel really motivated to change and want to capitalise on that to make a routine, while I still can.

Thanks!



Submitted October 16, 2018 at 06:25AM by hopeful_prince
via reddit https://ift.tt/2Ad20yl
